    <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-08-31 -->
    <a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2004-6/1129m.html#item13"
                    title="external link">
    Emulating Obsolete Document Formats
    </a>
    </font></h2>
    
    
    <p>
	<a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2004-6/1129m.html#item13">ACM News Service: NARA Conference Demonstrates Emulation Technologies</a>.&nbsp; The preservation of electronic documents is not so well-established as the archival preservation of printed materials, and emulation of no-longer available software implemented on no-longer-available platforms is one avenue for preservation of access.&nbsp; This blurb features the open-sourced <a href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/multivalent">Multivalent</a>, a Java-based universal document viewer (with plug-ins accepted) from Robert Wilensky's team at Berkeley, and GridForum's <a href="http://forge.gridforum.org/projects/dfdl-wg">DFDL</a> project for an XML-based Format Description Language that is useful for specifying how to pull data from binary-format document files.<br /><br />Joab Jackson's 2004-11-18 <a href="http://gcn.com/vol1_no1/daily-updates/27942-1.html"><em>Government Computer News</em> article</a> provides more discussion and links to the sources.
    </p>
	<span class="byline">posted by orcmid
